Comedic R&B. Dream soul. New jack swing. Quiet storm. And a little bit of chaos.

That‚Äôs how Tima Diakite (@timalikesmusic) describes the music she produces about relatable, funny everyday moments.

‚ÄúI love that feeling of waking up to R&B radio Sunday morning knowing you had to clean or waking up to gospel music. Whenever I‚Äôm creating music, I try to recapture that vibe.

How did I feel at my aunt‚Äôs wedding? How did I feel at my graduation cookout? I try to capture that because the Black experience, it‚Äôs like no other. I‚Äôm telling you, it‚Äôs a vibe.‚Äù

This Black History Month, we continue to #ShareBlackStories and celebrate Black joy in all its glory. üñ§

node.text:
‚ÄúI‚Äôm just a girl from DC with a passion and vision to tell inclusive stories that will hopefully inspire other audacious visionaries to dream big and go after what they want.‚Äù ‚Äî17-year-old actress, producer and filmmaker Lexi Underwood (@officiallexiunderwood)‚Å£
‚Å£
Lexi is living out her dream and creating space for others to do the same. This year, she‚Äôs one of the nominees at the NAACP Image Awards (@naacpimageawards), which celebrate outstanding achievements and performances in the Black community, an honor that Lexi takes serious pride in as she dedicates herself to amplifying Black stories.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúIf you can‚Äôt see it, you can‚Äôt be it. We normalize our stories by sharing them. When we fill these spaces and lean into our brilliance, Black stories are no longer reduced to ethnic experiences, anomalies or urban myths of mythical creatures.‚Å£
‚Å£
Our joyous, complex stories take center stage as a normalized way of life, connected to universal experiences that ultimately connect us to the human experience, where we find that we are more alike than we are different.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
Today on our story, Lexi highlights some of the women who inspire her every day.‚Å£
#ShareBlackStories üñ§‚Å£
‚Å£
Photo by @officiallexiunderwood

node.accessibility_caption: A person sitting on a picnic bench wearing jeans and a brown, pink and blue top; hills are in the background.

node.text:
‚ÄúI‚Äôve always wanted to stand out,‚Äù says 18-year-old Leo Mandella (@gullyguyleo). ‚ÄúI have never wanted to blend in with the so-called ‚Äònormal.‚Äô‚Äù As long as Leo can remember, he‚Äôs expressed himself everyday through fashion.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúThe way I put a look together is by thinking of everything. Everything could include where you‚Äôre going, who you‚Äôre seeing, what the environment you‚Äôre going to looks like.‚Å£
‚Å£
I like to match my color palettes in an outfit to my environment, as this makes it so much more effective. Always add your own personal twist on this.‚Å£
‚Å£
My main tip is to feel comfortable. Never force yourself into something because you think it looks best, because believe me, people can notice when you aren‚Äôt comfortable in your own drip.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
Photo by @gullyguyleo

node.accessibility_caption: An illustration of a person with their eyes closed and hands to their chin.

node.text:
‚ÄúInk is a historical tool for storytelling, and the strokes of the ball pen are to me what words are to any other storyteller,‚Äù explains Oscar Ukonu (@oscarukonu), whose detailed, hyper-realistic portraits are drawn with an everyday ballpoint pen. ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
‚ÄúMy style is a practice in time and patience,‚Äù says the Lagos-based artist, who works approximately 300 hours on a single piece. ‚ÄúMy work celebrates the diversity in the strength and richness of the African lived experiences and realities, which in many ways has been lost to the repetitive and underrepresented concept of ‚Äò'being Black‚Äô in this part of the world. ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Portraying African identities in my work is also an attempt to empower Black people in diaspora and shine light on the diverse ways of knowing and being for Black people in general.‚Äù ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Art and Video by @oscarukonu

node.text:
‚ÄúI would like to spread the message of hope and resilience by sharing my peoples‚Äô stories,‚Äù says 19-year-old advocate and multimedia artist Yang (@indigenousiconyang). ‚ÄúAs young people, we are often left out, doubted and ignored, but I want you to know: we are sacred, we are the dreams of our ancestors. We are the change we need in this world.‚Äù ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Yang began her advocacy journey at age 15 and three years later was leading thousands of young people in the 2019 global climate strike at the state capitol in New Mexico. ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
‚ÄúAs Indigenous people, we have never been given any opportunities to share our stories and identities,‚Äù says Yang, who is Din√© and Chicana from Din√©tah, the traditional homeland of the Navajo tribe.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúHistorically, my community, facing environmental racism, colonization, discrimination has been sacrificed for the development of the economy. I realized at a young age I had an important and sacred obligation to my people, to speak, make art and bring awareness to these social and environmental injustices. Because at the end of the day, we have to.‚Äù ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Photo of @indigenousiconyang by @charleykingphotography

node.accessibility_caption: A woman holding a basketball whips her bright blue braids in the air.

node.text:
‚ÄúBlack women get the short end of the stick, so to be as successful as I am, it means everything to me.‚Äù ‚ÄîUniversity of South Carolina student athlete Aliyah Boston (@aliyah.boston)‚Å£
‚Å£
Today, the sophomore leads her team (@gamecockwbb) into @ncaawbb #MarchMadness. Her hard work and dedication paid off in a No. 1 seed position for her team, plus Aliyah was named a first-team All-American.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúI hope that I‚Äôm able to inspire younger Black girls to have the confidence to play whatever sport they want,‚Äù explains Aliyah, who fights for equality on and off the court. ‚ÄúPush through every obstacle, because it‚Äôs not going to be easy.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
#ShareBlackStories üñ§ #SeeMe‚Å£
‚Å£
Photo of @aliyah.boston by @kevindliles for @sportsillustrated and @sifullframe
